What works, and what doesn't, in Connect mode.

The rule follows directly from the design. Anything that describes a serializable plan works. Anything that needs direct java-virtual-machine access from the client does not.

Start with what is supported — the dataframe and sequel surface. Dataframe and dataset operations work. Spark dot sequel works. Spark dot read and dataframe dot write work. The built-in functions work, and so do regular and pandas user-defined functions — because their code is shipped to the server and executed there. Structured streaming works, and the pandas interface on Spark works, both from version three point five onward.

Now what is not supported — anything reaching for the java virtual machine. Spark dot spark-context does not work, and neither does the whole R-D-D interface, like parallelize or R-D-D dot map, because there is no spark context on the client. The internal py-four-jay handles do not exist. And you cannot inject jars from the client — they have to be on the server's classpath.

One trap is worth naming. The two builders look identical, but they resolve to different classes — a classic session class, and a connect session class. If the spark-remote environment variable is set, get-or-create can hand you a connect session, even when your code looks classic.

Here is the exam takeaway. If a question mentions spark context, R-D-Ds, or client-side jars, that code is incompatible with Connect. If it sticks to dataframes, sequel, and user-defined functions, it works.
